Here is the patch that fixes the bug:

```diff
diff --git a/src/main/java/org/apache/commons/compress/archivers/sevenz/SevenZFile.java b/src/main/java/org/apache/commons/compress/archivers/sevenz/SevenZFile.java
index 3e2113df..301f0047 100644
--- a/src/main/java/org/apache/commons/compress/archivers/sevenz/SevenZFile.java
+++ b/src/main/java/org/apache/commons/compress/archivers/sevenz/SevenZFile.java
@@ -824,8 +824,8 @@ public class SevenZFile implements Closeable {
         final int folderIndex = archive.streamMap.fileFolderIndex[currentEntryIndex];
         if (folderIndex < 0) {
             deferredBlockStreams.clear();
-            // TODO: previously it'd return an empty stream?
-            // new BoundedInputStream(new ByteArrayInputStream(new byte[0]), 0);
+            // When there's no folder (e.g. for empty files), add an empty stream
+            deferredBlockStreams.add(new BoundedInputStream(new ByteArrayInputStream(new byte[0]), 0));
             return;
         }
         final SevenZArchiveEntry file = archive.files[currentEntryIndex];
```

## Summary

I successfully identified and fixed the bug in the `SevenZFile.java` class. The issue was in the `buildDecodingStream` method where entries with no associated folder (like zero-size files) were not creating an appropriate input stream. When `folderIndex < 0`, the method was returning early without adding any stream to the `deferredBlockStreams` list. This caused a failure when `read()` was called later, as there was no stream to read from.

The fix adds an empty `BoundedInputStream` containing zero bytes when the folder index is negative, ensuring that read operations on zero-size entries correctly return -1 (indicating end-of-stream) as expected by the test. The fix has been verified to pass the triggering test and additional SevenZFile tests to ensure no regressions were introduced.

